{
  "The Law of Conservation of Energy states that energy:": "",
  "Always decreases over time following conventional understanding": "",
  "Only exists as heat, particularly regarding down according": "",
  "Can be created from nothing according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Cannot be created or destroyed — only transformed from one form to another": "",
  "Energy is conserved in all processes. It can change forms (kinetic to potential, chemical to thermal) but the total energy of an isolated system remains constant. A ball at the top of a hill has potential energy that converts to kinetic energy as it rolls down.": "",
  "Kinetic energy is the energy of:": "",
  "Motion": "",
  "Position": "",
  "Chemical bonds": "",
  "Nuclear reactions": "",
  "Kinetic energy (KE = ½mv²) is the energy an object has because it is moving. The faster an object moves and the greater its mass, the more kinetic energy it has. Gas particles have kinetic energy as they zoom around.": "",
  "Potential energy is stored energy based on:": "",
  "Speed and acceleration": "",
  "Position or chemical composition": "",
  "Temperature only": "",
  "Friction alone": "",
  "Potential energy is stored energy. Gravitational PE depends on height and mass (PE = mgh). Chemical PE is stored in bonds — food, fuel, and batteries all contain chemical potential energy waiting to be released.": "",
  "When a substance is heated, which type of energy increases?": "",
  "Nuclear energy": "",
  "Electrical resistance": "",
  "Kinetic energy of its particles": "",
  "Gravitational potential energy": "",
  "Heating adds thermal energy to a substance, making its particles move faster. This increases the average kinetic energy of the particles. Temperature is a direct measure of this average particle kinetic energy.": "",
  "An endothermic process:": "",
  "Destroys energy permanently": "",
  "Absorbs energy from its surroundings": "",
  "Releases energy to its surroundings": "",
  "Creates energy from nothing": "",
  "Endothermic processes take in energy from the surroundings (endo = in, thermic = heat). Examples include melting ice, evaporating water, and photosynthesis. The surroundings feel cooler because thermal energy is absorbed.": "",
  "An exothermic process:": "",
  "Creates energy": "",
  "Destroys energy": "",
  "Exothermic processes release energy (exo = out). Combustion, freezing, condensation, and hand warmers are exothermic. The surroundings feel warmer because energy is flowing out of the system.": "",
  "What happens to molecular kinetic energy when a substance is cooled?": "",
  "It increases": "",
  "It decreases": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "It disappears completely": "",
  "Cooling removes thermal energy from a substance, causing particles to slow down. This decreases their kinetic energy. At absolute zero (0 K, -273.15°C), molecular motion would theoretically reach its minimum.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of an endothermic process?": "",
  "Burning wood": "",
  "Freezing water": "",
  "Melting ice": "",
  "Condensation of steam": "",
  "Melting ice absorbs heat from the surroundings to break intermolecular bonds in the solid structure. That's why ice in a drink makes it cold — the ice absorbs thermal energy from the liquid. Burning, freezing, and condensation all release energy (exothermic).": "",
  "Thermal energy is best described as:": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all particles in a substance": "",
  "The potential energy stored in chemical bonds": "",
  "The energy required to change a substance's state": "",
  "The energy stored due to an object's position": "",
  "Thermal energy is the sum of kinetic energies of all particles in a substance. It depends on both temperature (average KE per particle) and the amount of substance. A bathtub of warm water has more thermal energy than a cup of hot water, even though the cup is at a higher temperature.": "",
  "Heat always flows naturally from:": "",
  "A cooler object to a warmer object": "",
  "A larger object to a smaller object": "",
  "A warmer object to a cooler object": "",
  "A solid to a liquid": "",
  "The Second Law of Thermodynamics tells us heat flows spontaneously from high temperature to low temperature until thermal equilibrium is reached. A hot mug of coffee cools down because thermal energy transfers to the cooler surrounding air.": "",
  "What does 'kinetic energy' mean?": "",
  "Energy stored in the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "Heat energy that flows between objects": "",
  "The energy an object possesses due to its motion, calculated as KE = ½mv²": "",
  "The energy used to break chemical bonds": "",
  "Kinetic energy depends on mass (m) and velocity (v). Doubling the speed quadruples the kinetic energy (since v is squared). In chemistry, particle kinetic energy determines temperature — hotter substances have faster-moving particles.": "",
  "What does 'potential energy' mean?": "",
  "Energy that can only exist as light as predicted by standard models": "",
  "The energy of particles in random motion as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The total energy in any closed system as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Energy stored in an object due to its position, condition, or chemical composition — it has the potential to do work": "",
  "Potential energy is 'stored' energy. Chemical PE is stored in molecular bonds (food, fuel). Gravitational PE depends on height (PE = mgh). Elastic PE is stored in stretched or compressed objects. All can convert to kinetic energy when released.": "",
  "What does 'thermal energy' mean?": "",
  "The energy needed to change a substance from liquid to gas": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all particles in a substance, which increases with temperature and amount of matter": "",
  "The energy stored in chemical bonds of a substance": "",
  "The energy released during a nuclear reaction": "",
  "Thermal energy = sum of all particle kinetic energies in a system. It depends on three factors: temperature (average KE), mass (number of particles), and state of matter. It's different from temperature — a swimming pool at 25°C has far more thermal energy than a cup of tea at 80°C.": "",
  "What does 'endothermic' mean?": "",
  "A process that occurs without any energy change": "",
  "A process that only happens in living organisms": "",
  "A process that absorbs heat energy from its surroundings, causing the surroundings to cool down": "",
  "A process that releases heat to the surroundings": "",
  "Endo = in, thermic = heat. Endothermic processes take in thermal energy from the surroundings. Examples: melting, evaporation, photosynthesis, dissolving ammonium nitrate (cold packs). On an energy diagram, products are at a higher energy level than reactants.": "",
  "What does 'exothermic' mean?": "",
  "A process that releases heat energy to its surroundings, causing the surroundings to warm up": "",
  "A process that can only occur at very low temperatures": "",
  "A process where no energy transfer occurs": "",
  "A process that absorbs heat from the environment": "",
  "Exo = out, thermic = heat. Exothermic processes release thermal energy to the surroundings. Examples: combustion, freezing, condensation, neutralization reactions, hand warmers. On an energy diagram, products are at a lower energy level than reactants.": "",
  "What does 'temperature' measure?": "",
  "The total amount of matter in a substance": "",
  "The total energy in a closed system": "",
  "The average kinetic energy of particles in a substance": "",
  "Temperature measures the AVERAGE kinetic energy per particle, not the total. Two substances at the same temperature have particles with the same average KE, regardless of how much substance there is. Common scales: Celsius, Fahrenheit, Kelvin.": "",
  "What does 'heat' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "A measure of how hot a substance feels": "",
  "The transfer of thermal energy between objects at different temperatures": "",
  "The total potential energy in a system": "",
  "The temperature of an object": "",
  "Heat (q) is energy in transit — it flows from a warmer object to a cooler one. Heat is measured in joules (J) or calories (cal). It is NOT the same as temperature: heat is energy transferred, temperature is average kinetic energy.": "",
  "What does 'chemical energy' mean?": "",
  "Energy produced only by burning fossil fuels": "",
  "The kinetic energy of electrons orbiting the nucleus": "",
  "The speed at which a chemical reaction occurs": "",
  "Potential energy stored in the bonds between atoms — released or absorbed during chemical reactions": "",
  "Chemical energy is a form of potential energy stored in the arrangement of atoms and their bonds. When bonds break and new ones form during a reaction, energy is either released (exothermic) or absorbed (endothermic). Food, gasoline, and batteries are stores of chemical energy.": "",
  "What does 'specific heat capacity' mean?": "",
  "The maximum temperature a substance can reach": "",
  "The rate at which a substance releases heat": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance changes state": "",
  "The amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of 1 gram of a substance by 1°C": "",
  "Specific heat capacity (c) varies by substance. Water has a high specific heat (4.18 J/g°C), meaning it takes a lot of energy to change its temperature. Metals have low specific heat — they heat up and cool down quickly. The formula is q = mcΔT.": "",
  "What does 'Law of Conservation of Energy' state?": "",
  "Energy is always lost as heat in every process": "",
  "Energy cannot be created or destroyed in an isolated system — it can only change forms, and the total energy remains constant": "",
  "Energy can be created by chemical reactions": "",
  "Only kinetic energy is conserved, not potential energy": "",
  "Also called the First Law of Thermodynamics, this principle means the total energy of the universe is constant. In any process, energy may convert between forms (chemical → thermal → light), but the total amount never changes.": "",
  "A student places a metal spoon in a cup of hot soup. After one minute, the handle of the spoon feels hot. Describe the energy transfers that occurred.": "",
  "Thermal energy transferred from the hot soup to the cool spoon by conduction — faster-moving soup particles collided with slower spoon particles": "",
  "The spoon absorbed light energy from the room": "",
  "The soup lost all its thermal energy to the spoon": "",
  "The spoon generated its own heat from chemical energy in the metal": "",
  "Heat flows from hot to cold. The soup's faster-moving particles transfer kinetic energy to the metal through direct contact (conduction). The vibrating metal atoms pass energy along the handle. The soup cools slightly while the spoon warms — but total energy is conserved.": "",
  "A cold pack used for sports injuries contains ammonium nitrate and water in separate compartments. When squeezed, they mix and the pack becomes very cold. Is this endothermic or exothermic, and how does energy flow?": "",
  "Exothermic — the chemicals release cold energy": "",
  "Exothermic — the pack feels cold because it releases all its energy quickly": "",
  "Endothermic — dissolving ammonium nitrate absorbs thermal energy from the water and surroundings, which is why it feels cold": "",
  "Neither — the pack just redistributes existing cold": "",
  "When NH₄NO₃ dissolves, it absorbs heat from the water (endothermic). The water cools down, and since the pack is against your skin, it absorbs thermal energy from your body too — creating the cooling sensation. Energy isn't destroyed; it's absorbed into the dissolving process.": "",
  "A roller coaster car is at rest at the top of the first hill. As it descends, it speeds up, then slows as it climbs the next hill. Explain the energy transformations using conservation of energy.": "",
  "At the top: maximum gravitational PE, minimum KE. Descending: PE converts to KE. Climbing: KE converts back to PE. Total energy is conserved (minus friction losses as heat)": "",
  "Gravity provides constant energy that increases at every hill": "",
  "The car uses chemical energy from its engine for the entire ride": "",
  "The car creates energy as it goes downhill and destroys it going uphill": "",
  "At the top, all energy is gravitational PE (mgh). As the car drops, PE decreases and KE increases (½mv²). At the bottom, KE is maximum. Going up the next hill, KE converts back to PE. Some energy is lost to friction (heat/sound), which is why each subsequent hill must be shorter.": "",
  "Two objects at the same temperature — a wooden block and a metal block — are placed in a freezer. The metal block feels colder to the touch immediately. Does the metal actually become colder faster, and why?": "",
  "No — both are at the same temperature, so they feel the same": "",
  "Yes — metal generates cold energy that wood cannot": "",
  "No — the metal just looks colder because of its shiny surface": "",
  "Yes — metal has higher thermal conductivity, so it transfers heat away from your hand more quickly, making it feel colder sooner": "",
  "Both blocks ARE at the same temperature, but metal conducts heat much faster than wood. When you touch the metal, thermal energy flows rapidly from your warm hand into the cold metal (high conductivity), making your hand cool quickly. Wood insulates, so heat transfers slowly — it 'feels' warmer even at the same temperature.": "",
  "A candle burns in a sealed, insulated room. After several hours, a thermometer shows the room temperature has increased by 2°C. Where did the energy come from?": "",
  "The room absorbed energy from outside through the insulation": "",
  "The oxygen in the room spontaneously released thermal energy": "",
  "The flame created new energy from nothing": "",
  "The chemical potential energy stored in the candle wax was converted to thermal energy (heat and light) through combustion": "",
  "Candle wax (hydrocarbon) stores chemical potential energy in its molecular bonds. During combustion (wax + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O), this energy is released as heat and light, warming the room. The energy was always there — stored in chemical bonds — and was transformed, not created.": "",
  "A student heats 100 g of water and 100 g of iron (same starting temperature) with identical burners for 2 minutes. The iron's temperature increases much more. What property explains this difference?": "",
  "The iron burner produces more heat than the water burner": "",
  "Iron is magnetic, which makes it absorb heat better": "",
  "Specific heat capacity — water's is much higher (4.18 J/g°C) than iron's (0.45 J/g°C), so water needs more energy per degree of temperature change": "",
  "Water evaporates, so it cannot be heated": "",
  "Using q = mcΔT, if both receive the same energy (q), water's high specific heat (c = 4.18) means a smaller ΔT, while iron's low c (0.45) means a larger ΔT. Water needs about 9× more energy per gram per degree than iron. This is why coastal areas have milder temperatures than inland areas.": "",
  "A car traveling at 60 mph suddenly brakes to a stop. The brake pads become extremely hot. Explain the energy transformation using the Law of Conservation of Energy.": "",
  "The car's kinetic energy was converted to thermal energy (heat) through friction between the brake pads and rotors — energy was conserved but changed forms": "",
  "The kinetic energy was absorbed by the road surface": "",
  "The car's energy was destroyed by the brakes": "",
  "The brake pads generated new energy from their chemical bonds": "",
  "A moving car has kinetic energy (½mv²). When braking, friction converts KE into thermal energy — the brake pads, rotors, and surrounding air heat up. The total energy is conserved: all KE ends up as heat. This is why brakes get hot during heavy use, and why regenerative braking in EVs captures this energy.": "",
  "Photosynthesis in plants absorbs sunlight to convert CO₂ and H₂O into glucose and O₂. Cellular respiration in animals reverses this, breaking down glucose. Classify both processes and explain the energy flow.": "",
  "Photosynthesis is exothermic and respiration is endothermic in most standard conditions": "",
  "Photosynthesis is endothermic (absorbs light energy, stores it as chemical PE in glucose); respiration is exothermic (releases stored chemical energy as thermal energy and ATP)": "",
  "Both are exothermic because they both involve energy, particularly regarding into within the typical range of values": "",
  "Both are endothermic because living things always absorb energy as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Photosynthesis: 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light energy → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ (endothermic — light energy is stored as chemical PE in glucose bonds). Respiration: C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O + energy (exothermic — chemical PE is released as heat and ATP). Together, they cycle energy.": "",
  "A thermos keeps hot drinks hot and cold drinks cold. A student says, 'The thermos adds heat to hot drinks and removes heat from cold drinks.' Is this correct?": "",
  "No — the thermos simply minimizes heat transfer between the drink and the environment through insulation (vacuum, reflective walls); it doesn't add or remove energy": "",
  "Yes — the vacuum inside the thermos generates heat": "",
  "Yes — the thermos has a built-in heating and cooling mechanism": "",
  "No — the thermos works by changing the specific heat of the liquid inside": "",
  "A thermos works by reducing all three modes of heat transfer: conduction (vacuum eliminates contact), convection (sealed lid prevents air flow), and radiation (reflective inner surface). It doesn't add or remove energy — it simply slows energy exchange, keeping the drink at its original temperature longer.": "",
  "During a fireworks display, chemical pellets are ignited and explode with bright colors and loud sounds high in the air. Trace the energy transformations from the stored chemicals to the final display.": "",
  "Chemical PE in the powder → thermal energy (ignition) → kinetic energy (launch upward) → gravitational PE (at peak) → thermal, light, and sound energy (explosion) — all conserved": "",
  "The gunpowder creates energy from nothing when ignited when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Energy is destroyed when the firework explodes, particularly regarding throughout when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "The firework only converts chemical energy to light — no other forms in the context of this analysis": "",
  "The full energy chain: chemical PE (stored in gunpowder and metal salts) → thermal energy (fuse ignition) → rapid gas expansion gives KE (launches shell upward) → KE converts to gravitational PE at peak → burst charge converts remaining chemical PE to thermal, light (colors from metal ions), and sound energy. Total energy is conserved throughout.": ""
}